French court rejects proposal to demolish shops in Jungle refugee camp
A French court has rejected a proposal by Calais authorities to demolish dozens of convenience stores and restaurants in the Jungle camp, home to thousands of refugees.
In a court hearing this week, Calais officials argued that the state should demolish 72 shops where people in the camp sold a variety of products, from cigarettes to energy drinks, cut their hair or sold basic food for 50 cents (40p) for tea or a few euros.
The Calais Governorate argued that these sites should be demolished because they create a parallel economy that is tax-free and carries fire and hygiene risks.
The charity groups told the court that shops and restaurants were vital, and that free food provided by state-sponsored organizations and other groups was not enough for the growing population in the camp.
They argued that convenience stores and restaurants often provide shelter and free food to those in need.
A court in Lille ruled that there was no legal basis for the deportation of the 72-barrel shop owners, but the concerns of the governor of Calais were "fully understandable".
Judge Jean-François Molla said that grocery stores, cafes and restaurants were doing more than just feeding people living in "extremely dangerous conditions".
He said these areas provide comfortable meeting points for refugees and volunteers.
One of the places in danger of being destroyed is the non-profit Jungle Book Cafe for Children, which serves 200 meals a day, offers English and French classes, and provides asylum advice to hundreds of underage refugees in the camp.
Over 170,000 people have signed a petition to protect this children's cafe.
A letter to the Guardian said the closure would be "a disaster for these children, some of whom are as young as eight".
Two charities, Help Refugees and L'Auberge des Migrants, estimated on Friday that the population in the Jungle camp had risen to over 9,000 (the highest ever) after the number of arrivals increased during the summer.
