Bulgaria released inflation figures for the first time in 8 months
According to national statistics, monthly inflation in Bulgaria was at 1 percent in June.
This is the highest value in years (since June 2012) and the first value above zero since October, after a positive value of 0.2% last year.
The average annual inflation rate measured by the CPI for the last 12 months (August 2015 - July 2016) was -0.8% compared to the previous 12 months (August 2014 - July 2015).
The consumer price index in July 2016 was 101.0% compared to June 2016, i.e. monthly inflation was 1.0%.
The inflation rate since the beginning of the year (comparison of July 2016 to December 2015) was -0.2%, and the monthly inflation difference between July 2016 and July 2015 was -0.2%.
In July 2016, compared to the previous month, price increases were observed in the following consumer product groups: food and non-alcoholic beverages (1.7%), transport (1.8%), entertainment and culture (6.3%), restaurants and hotels (1.2%), various goods and services (0.3%).
Prices fell in the clothing and footwear (2.2%), furniture, household equipment and routine care (0.5%) and healthcare (0.1%).
Prices for alcoholic beverages and tobacco products, housing, water, electricity, gas and other fuels, communications and education remained the same.
Snapchat "anime" effect criticized as Asian cartoon
While Snapchat claims to be inspired by animation for this filter, some observers have expressed that it is racially insensitive.
Snapchat enables 150 million users every day to play with their identities on an absurd level, altering their reality through the lens.
You can turn yourself into a pineapple, a dog, or a character jumping out of a painting by Roy Lichtenstein.
Lenses are reckless, feature-changing devices that generate over 30 million enhanced gravitational waves every day.
Misplaced steps are quickly etched into the public memory.
Snapchat lenses have faced accusations in the past that the app promotes black classification or presents bleached skin tones as a beauty ideal.
So, because of the lens they introduced this week, which left users with squinting eyes, broken teeth and puffy cheeks, some critics criticized the company as being an "Asian mask" that caricatured Asians.
And they wondered if these recurring conflicts pointed to a bigger problem with the company's diversity.
The news and fury spread with news from The Verge and Motherboard on Wednesday, and Snapchat announced the feature was removed a day later.
The company made a statement: The mirror was not designed to caricature Asians, but to honor the anime characters.
But for observers with experience in racism, the lens reminded them of painful stereotypes.
Others have generally rejected the anime comparison.
Grace Sparapani, a Korean-American art student whose tweet about the photos was widely shared, said in an email that the lens was "painful and uncomfortable in the slightest".
"It's hard to argue when it comes to comparing the effects of the bad Asian cartoon and the filter side by side", he added.
Which means that the filter is not just an Asian mask, but a degradingly Asian mask.
Snapchat isn't the only company that's overcome cultural triggers.
American culture seems to be in a constant struggle for diversity and inclusion in many areas, from corporate boardrooms to Hollywood and the devices we all carry in our hands.
And the broad youth audience that Snapchat is addressing, which is more racially diverse than its other counterparts, can also be interpreted as having a higher sensitivity expectation.
In an interview on Thursday, 25-year-old Katie Zhu said that when one of Snapchat's lenses creates a demeaning image for a user, "it's much harder not to notice that kind of behavior as it used to be".
On Thursday, Ms. Zhu, a product manager and engineer for Medium, decided to delete her Snapchat account and called everyone to do the same.
In an article for Medium and a telephone interview, she stated that she believed the race conflicts reflected a lack of diversity in Snapchat's hiring practices.
Ms. Zhu ended her article by criticizing the company's leadership team, which is mostly made up of white men, with a tag: #SnapchatiSilin.
"Either the different races in the staff are not sufficiently diverse to make such decisions", said Ms. Zhu, an American of Chinese descent, "or the people who work there are not safe or comfortable enough to talk".
Other observers share his views on the complaint, which Snapchat largely left unanswered.
The company is not sharing figures on diversity among its staff, emphasizing its private company status.
On Thursday, Snapchat declined to share the racial origins of its staff, but according to a spokesperson, the company recently added a hiring manager to its staff to focus on underrepresented populations and increase its internal inclusion efforts.
Ms. Zhu, for her part, stated that she would keep her Snapchat account off, adding, "I wonder if they need more users like us who can say that this is not true".
Congress panel says military officials misrepresented ISIS intelligence
In a report released Thursday, a congressional panel reported that United States Central Command officials misrepresented intelligence reports to paint a more optimistic picture of the war against the Islamic State in Iraq and Syria than the events on the ground.
An interim report prepared by a working group of Republican council presidents from the House Armed Services Committee, Intelligence Committee and Defense Appropriations Subcommittee found "widespread dissatisfaction" among Central Command intelligence analysts who said their superiors had altered assessments of Islamic State by American forces.
Central Command, known as Centcom, is a military headquarters located in Tampa, Fla., that oversees U.S. military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
A news release on the report stated: "Intelligence findings confirmed by senior Centcom leaders typically paint a more positive picture of U.S. counterterrorism efforts than the facts on the ground and consistently yield far more positive results than analyses by other elements of the intelligence community".
California Republican Representative Ken Calvert said, "What happened at Centcom is unacceptable, and our combat troops are suffering from poor analysis of the top decision makers".
The failure of the leadership at Centcom has reached the highest levels of the organization.
The 10-page report also details the ongoing problems in 2014 and 2015 that were part of the Central Command's explanation and analysis of the U.S. training efforts for Iraqi forces.
Although there is no concrete evidence that senior Obama administration officials ordered the reports to be altered, analysts are reportedly feeling pressure from Centcom leaders to offer a more optimistic view of the threat posed by ISIS and the Islamic State, also known as ISIS.
The report states that "in the first half of 2015, many Central Command press releases, statements and congressional statements were significantly more positive than actual events".
For example, a Centcom official has publicly stated that a major military offensive to retake Mosul could be launched as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul, Iraq's second largest city, is still under the control of the Islamic State.
Republican Representative Mike Pompeo of Kansas said in a statement that "after months of research, this is now quite clearly understood".
From mid-2014 to mid-2015, the most senior intelligence leaders of the United States Central Command manipulated the intelligence results of the commander to paint the threat posed by ISIS in Iraq as insignificant.
Republicans have formed a task force after analysts raised concerns about the manipulation of intelligence on the Islamic State.
As the review continues, the report, released Thursday, will follow much more comprehensive findings.
There is another Centcom intelligence review being conducted by the DOD Inspector General.
The Democratic members of the House Intelligence Committee also released their own findings Thursday, which agree with some of the conclusions reached by the Republican task force.
The committee's Democratic chairman, Representative Adam B. Schiff, said in a statement that "between 2014 and 2015, Centcom has formed an extremely narrow-minded process in its intelligence assessments of ISIS and Iraqi Security Forces".
According to Mr. Schiff, this process "has delayed the release of intelligence results", has led to a breakdown in morale among analysts, and has "not given enough room for contrary opinions".
However, Mr. Schiff and the Democrats have said they have not found any evidence that the White House pressured Centcom analysts into fabricating the results of a "predetermined or political narrative".
The preliminary results of the congressional review were announced by the Daily Beast on Tuesday.
Last August, the New York Times reported that a Pentagon inspector general's review was available following complaints by Centcom analysts.
Lt. Commander Patrick Evans, a Pentagon spokesman, said in a statement that the inspector general would not comment on the DOD congressional report while the review continues.
However, he said that "experts may disagree on the interpretation of complex data in some cases, and the intelligence community and the Department of Defense support healthy dialogue on these important national security issues".
The research will echo beyond the question of whether the American-led bombing operation in Iraq and Syria is continuing (an argument raised by more and more Defense officials every day).
But the accusations made last year have raised questions about how much President Obama can trust the Central Command to make honest assessments of military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya and other hot spots.
Criticism of the Islamic State's intelligence coverage began when Centcom intelligence analyst Gregory Hooker wrote an article stating that the administration of President George W. Bush had advocated a small force presence in Iraq despite the objections of many analysts and had not given enough thought to the aftermath of the 2003 invasion, and has been debated for more than a decade.
Mr. Hooker also played a key role in the insurgency against Islamic State intelligence.
Officials said they concluded that despite public statements to the contrary last year, Mr. Hooker's team concluded that the airstrikes against refineries held by ISIS had not significantly affected the financial resources of the terrorist group, as they had built temporary refineries to sell oil on the black market.
But as The Times reported in September, the findings were not outside Central Command.
The Senate statement last year by then-Commander of Centcom, General Lloyd J. Austin III, was criticized by many lawmakers as a highly positive assessment of the war.
General Austin retired in April and was succeeded in the Central Command by General Joseph L. Votel.
