Starting next June, these legal aid centers are scheduled to be stripped of more than 30 percent of their federal funding.
James Farrel, Queensland Director of Community Legal Support Centres, reported that the latest Census Report of the National Association of Community Legal Support Centres found that thousands of people are turned away every year.
Mr. Farrel has stated that the situation will get much worse if the federal government's decision is not reversed.
"Queensland's community legal support centres are chronically under-supported financially, which means thousands of people are not able to access the vital services they need", he said.
People in violent relationships, people struggling with the forces that are breaking the government, families in the process of separation, and workers unfairly dismissed -- all of these are facing problems with legal dimensions and are not getting the help they need, according to this report.
The federal government will cut funding by 30 percent from June 2017, which means thousands of vulnerable Queenslanders will have to deal with more complex legal issues without help.
We call on the Minister of Justice and Senator George Brandis of Queensland to immediately withdraw these funding cuts so that people can get the support they need when they face a legal problem.
