NASA climate model: Venus was once habitable
The new NASA climate model predicts that Venus once had conditions that were habitable.
Scientists at NASA's Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model to explore the past of Venus using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to determine whether Venus, with its hot, water-free surface and CO2-filled atmosphere, once hosted conditions similar to those on Earth.
Scientists have explained Venus' low rotational velocity in the past with its thick atmosphere.
But recent estimates suggest that Venus may have had a thin, Earth-like atmosphere and still be spinning slowly.
The model also looked at the topography of ancient Venus.
Although your planet has more dry areas than Earth, it may once have had enough water and protection from rapid evaporation with geographical variability.
The old Venus was also benefiting from a 30% dimmer sun.
"The slow rotation of Venus in the simulation of the GISS model caused the day side of Venus to face the sun for almost two months at a time", said Anthony Del Genio, a GISS scientist, in a news release.
This heated the surface, causing rain to form thick layers of clouds that act as an umbrella to protect the surface from the heat from the sun.
As a result, the average climate temperatures were only a few degrees colder than the Earth is today.
The model allowed for a story similar to the evolutionary hypothesis that planetary scientists had previously put forward for Venus.
Although once habitable, Venus has been exposed to a lot of heat and ultraviolet light over the course of several billion years.
Their oceans evaporated and the water vapor was destroyed by UV radiation.
The hydrogen ran out, leaving only a thick atmosphere of carbon dioxide, with its deadly greenhouse effect, the Venus we know today.
The researchers shared the results of the new Venus climate model in their Geophysical Research Papers.
