Kepler has measured the rotation speed of stars in the constellation of Ur
With its latest mission, the Kepler space telescope has helped astronomers create the most complete catalog of stars in the constellation of Uranus in terms of their rotational velocities.
The new data are helping astronomers understand why stars in the constellation rotate at varying speeds and how their rotation periods relate to planet formation.
Luisa Rebull, a research scientist at Caltech's Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis in Pasadena, said in a news release: "When we compare our results with star clusters, we hope to learn more about the relationship between the mass of a star, its age, and even the history of the solar system".
The planetary constellation is 445 light-years from Earth.
Most of the stars in the constellation formed 125 million years ago and are reaching a new stage of maturity.
They're spinning at the fastest speed they've ever been in their lives.
At peak spin speeds, stars in this maturing stage form large amounts of stellar wind.
These winds create a refractive effect on the stars as they move through the magnetic fields of the stars.
As a star ages, its spin rate starts to decrease.
Kepler measures the rotation speed of each star by tracking the time between the appearance of visible star spots, such as sunspots.
The latest catalog of spin speeds suggests that larger stars spin faster than smaller stars.
Rebull likened the stars to dancers, stating that the large ones performed their single-legged turns more slowly than the small ones.
Rebull said, "In the ball of the planet, we see that the slow-spinning stars are much heavier, and the fast-spinning ones are very light".
Because the planet is so close to the constellation, it serves as an ideal cosmic laboratory for comparing stellar properties and spin speeds.
Rebull said, "The young and old of the Milky Way constellation provides theoretical models for stellar rotations in both directions".
There's more to learn about how, when and why stars drop their spin speeds, why they put their "dancing shoes" in a corner, so to speak.
Rebull and his colleagues have detailed their latest analysis of the spin velocities of the constellation Ulker in three new papers to be published shortly in the Journal of Astronomy.
